                    <abstract lang="eng">This paper comments on a talk given by Verena Risse at the 2018 ZiF Workshop &quot;Studying Migration Policies at the Interface Between Empirical Research and Normative Analysis&quot;, September 2018, in Bielefeld. Risse describes three general concepts of how border control tends to deviate from the standard case of a state official performing control at the geographical border. Then, she attempts to establish that these developments create a situation that is not covered by classical approaches of the normative justification of border controls. Though I agree with many of Risse’s observations, I doubt that there is a straightforward link from those three general concepts to normative problems. Therefore, if we want to evaluate border policies, we need a much more fine-grained apparatus of, on the one hand, normative principles, and, on the other hand, information about the nature and consequences of these border policies. Risse’s paper is available under doi: 10.17879/95189433777.</abstract>
